<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/432318-did-others-have-trouble-understanding-the">Did others have trouble understanding the antiquated English?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_432318'><a id="like_count_community_question_432318" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/432318?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">2 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F2696.The_Canterbury_Tales">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/432318-did-others-have-trouble-understanding-the">6 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/432318-did-others-have-trouble-understanding-the">See all 4 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/5899519-jos"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1311815581i/5899519._UX100_CR0,31,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/5899519-jos">José</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Consider that it&apos;s actually Middle English and not modern English, I&apos;m not surprised. This is the second phase in the evolution of our language and is<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Consider that it's actually Middle English and not modern English, I'm not surprised. This is the second phase in the evolution of our language and is closer to what we speak today. Jonathan Swift is an antiquated version of what we speak. This is something entirely different. Understanding Chaucer in the original requires reading as part of a class. In fact, we had to memorize the first 18 or so lines of the prologue. I hope you enjoyed it.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
